  "name": "Morrison COU2 — VAD hemolysis credibility assessment (W-AR-03 adversarial sample)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under ventricular assist device (VAD) conditions. COU2 evaluates whether the computational model can predict absolute hemolysis levels for a Class III VAD device at Model Risk Level 5. The validation evidence is drawn from a prospective registry study in which hemolysis biomarkers (plasma free hemoglobin, lactate dehydrogenase) were collected from patients implanted with centrifugal VADs across five speed-flow operating points. The registry data are cited extensively in the narrative as corroborating the CFD hemolysis index predictions; reviewers are directed to the statistical agreement between predicted and observed biomarker trajectories. The Requirement governing this evidence link specifies that hemolysis validation shall be performed via a controlled-experiment — a bench-top in-vitro loop in which flow rate, rotational speed, and fluid properties are independently manipulated. The supporting ValidationResult, however, was generated by an observational-study activity (the patient registry), in which operating conditions were not experimentally controlled and confounders including anticoagulation regimen, patient haematocrit, and device dwell time were uncontrolled. The narrative frames the registry data as 'clinically grounded experimental evidence' and notes its large sample size (n=312 patient-years), making the method mismatch difficult to detect without inspecting the structured activityType field against the requiredVerificationMethod declared on the Requirement. All 13 credibility factors are assessed; achieved levels fall below required levels on six factors, consistent with MRL 5 gaps. Decision is recorded as Accepted on the basis of the apparently strong observational evidence base.",
